<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/0486e81cd120c13793f644fda8028f7d> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#name> "OFFERSTANDAARD BESCHILDERD MET DIEREN EN DEMONEN" .
<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/0486e81cd120c13793f644fda8028f7d> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Dit houten plateau op voet is een 'dulang'. Ze worden op Bali veelvuldig gebruikt en dienen als presenteerblad voor zowel offers als voor priesterattributen. Deze dulang is voorzien van bijzondere motieven die geaccentueerd zijn met goudverf. Op de bovenkant zijn demonenhoofden met vlammen te zien. Het demonenhoofd in het midden is afgebeeld met beide handen in een symbolische houding. Het onderste deel van het blad is versierd met dieren in twee paren: een leeuw tegenover een stier en een leeuw tegenover een varken. Vanwege deze bijzondere motieven is het aannemelijk dat een priester deze dulang heeft gebruikt om zijn attributen, zoals de priesterbel en het vat voor heilig water op te zetten. \r\n\r\nThe dulang, or footed wooden tray, is one of the commonest of Balinese wooden artefacts, and is found in almost every home. Its diameter varies from about 20 cm to over 50 cm, its height being in rough proportion to the diameter. The top tray section usually has a slightly raised rim 2-3 cm broad. It always has a flaring foot. It usually is made out of a single piece of wood. The dulang exhibited here, of average size, is typical in all these respects. Many dulang are left as plain wood, some are painted black (especially those from Lombok), others are painted and decorated with geometric and plant designs. Exceptional are those dulang which are decorated with painted animals or human figures illustrating or reflecting a particular story. \r\n\tThis dulang is elaborately painted over a base colour of red. On the upper surface of the tray, there is a central figure of a demonic kala head, such as is found above temple gateways, with the usual accompanying pair of hands whose fingers here are in mudra-like positions. Surrounding it are alternating figures of four fiery demonic heads (often called gelap) and four triangular-shaped flame ornaments. On the underside of the tray, alternating with pomegranate designs, are four animal figures arranged in two pairs: a lion facing a bull, and a lion facing a dog or jackal (or pig?).  The depiction of these animals does not tell a particular story but refers in a general way to the famous group of animal tales known in Bali as Tantri (Pancatantra in India), where these animals play significant roles. Tantri stories are common themes in sculpture and painting.  \r\n\tA dulang has various uses. Its original purpose is probably as a utensil for serving food, as is still the case in parts of Bali.  Four or more people sit in a circle around the dulang, which is piled high with rice and side dishes, their right hands facing towards it. It is now probably most often used as a base for food offerings. It is also used as a tray on which a priest places his (or her) ritual utensils, such as bell and holy water vessel. The beautifully decorated dulang presented here is said to have served such a purpose, and this view is supported not only by its artistic qualities, but also by the mudra-like fingers of the central kala head.  \r\nFrancine Brinkgreve" .
